        <p class="text-lg mb-8">
          Looking for reliable and energy-efficient heating solutions? Our certified Electricians in Croydon specialize in Electric Underfloor Heating systems—designed for modern homes, renovations, and eco-conscious homeowners.
        </p>
        <a href="#contact" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center px-8 py-4 bg-green text-white rounded-2xl font-medium text-lg hover:bg-dark hover:text-white transition-all">
          Get Free Quote — 020 3519 9989
        </a>
      </div>
      <div class="[content-visibility:auto] [contain-intrinsic-size:400px] relative">
        <div class="bg-green rounded-[45px] p-1 md:p-2 relative z-10">
          <Image src={seoImg} alt="Electric Underfloor Heating Installation in Croydon" class="w-full h-auto rounded-[35px]" />
        </div>
        <div class="absolute top-8 left-8 right-8 bottom-8 bg-dark rounded-[45px] -z-10"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHAT IS ELECTRIC UNDERFLOOR HEATING -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-gray px-4">
    <div class="max-w-screen-xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-medium mb-6">What Is Electric Underfloor Heating?</h2>
      <p class="mb-6">
        Electric underfloor heating uses heating cables or mats installed beneath your flooring to deliver efficient, evenly distributed warmth. Electric underfloor heating works by passing an electric current through these cables or wires, causing them to heat up and radiate warmth into the room. It eliminates the need for radiators and frees up wall space, offering a sleek and silent alternative.
      </p>
      <p>
        There are different types of electric underfloor heating, such as mats and loose wire systems, each suited to different installation needs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- TYPES OF UNDERFLOOR HEATING -->
  <section class="py-20 px-4">
    <div class="max-w-screen-xl mx-auto grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-center">
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-medium mb-6">Types of Underfloor Heating: Electric vs. Water-Based</h2>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full border-collapse text-left">
            <thead class="bg-dark text-white">
              <tr>
                <th class="p-4">Feature</th>
                <th class="p-4">Electric</th>
                <th class="p-4">Water-Based</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="bg-gray">
              <tr><td class="p-4">Installation Cost</td><td class="p-4">Lower</td><td class="p-4">Higher</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="p-4">Ideal For</td><td class="p-4">Retrofits & small areas</td><td class="p-4">New builds & large spaces</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="p-4">Response Time</td><td class="p-4">Fast</td><td class="p-4">Slower</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="p-4">Maintenance</td><td class="p-4">Minimal</td><td class="p-4">Regular servicing</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Electric systems are ideal for quick installations and smaller spaces, while water-based systems are better suited for larger or new-build properties. For water-based underfloor heating, a qualified plumber is required to connect the system to the manifold and perform a pressure test to check for leaks and ensure safe, proper operation before the pipes are covered.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Careful planning and preparation are essential for any underfloor heating project, regardless of the system type.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <Image src={seoImg} alt="Underfloor Heating Types Comparison" class="rounded-[35px]" loading="lazy" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- MATERIALS AND TOOLS NEEDED -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-gray px-4">
    <div class="max-w-screen-xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-medium mb-6">Materials and Tools Needed</h2>
      <p class="mb-6">
        To successfully install an electric underfloor heating system, having the right materials and tools on hand is essential. You'll need an electric underfloor heating mat or loose cable, depending on your chosen system, as well as insulation boards to maximize heat efficiency and minimize energy loss. A reliable thermostat and floor sensor are crucial for precise temperature control, while power supply cables connect your underfloor heating system safely to the mains supply.
      </p>
      <p>
        For the installation process, basic tools such as a tape measure for accurate floor area measurement, a multimeter for electrical testing, and wire cutters for preparing cables are required. A qualified electrician should always handle the final electrical connections to ensure your heating system is installed correctly and safely, meeting all regulatory standards.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PRE-INSTALLATION PREPARATION -->
  <section class="py-20 px-4">
    <div class="max-w-screen-xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-medium mb-6">Pre-Installation Preparation</h2>
      <p class="mb-6">
